Harvard students take a break from school
This year, Harvard University has launched a new course that allows all undergraduates to get more sleep and fights the growing male-dominated trend of studying with caffeine all night.
One professor noticed that most students at the best university in the world don't know how to take care of themselves
The course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that he came up with the idea.
At the end, a student came up to me and said, "Why do you only tell me this in the last year?"
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being offered for the first time this year, teaches students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's chief medical officer, said the university decided to introduce the course after noticing that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course time consists of various interactive exercises.
One section presents an image of a dormitory containing various objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books, etc.) which students click on to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
 We know that this will not change students' behaviour instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know this information - just as you have a right to know what the health effects of smoking are,  added Professor Czeisler.
He says that the culture of pride in staying up late is still there, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students are making sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Getting enough good quality sleep should be the secret weapon of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, leaving them permanently hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California chemistry and physical biology student, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year during his freshman year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and had led him to insist that it be offered throughout the campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar programme of study before joining the reputed institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students have an alarm for both bedtime and wake-up time and be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythms and lead to sleep disturbances.
