Germany's new warship still delayed
According to local media, the new German Navy frigate was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the aging Cold War warships, but it will not be commissioned until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential spending.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes a military spokesman, the commissioning of the  Rheinland-Pfalz , the flagship of the newly-launched frigates of Baden-Württemberg, has been postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship was supposed to join the Navy in 2014, but the troubling issues that arose after delivery compromised the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles and some stealth technologies, such as a radar, infrared and reduced acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to deploy the newest frigates for up to two years outside home ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the constant delays mean that the advanced warships - which should enable Germany to project its power overseas - will already be obsolete when they are put into service.
Last year, the cursed F125 frigate made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
The reasons for this return were not well known, but German media mentioned a number of  software and hardware defects  that rendered the warship useless in case of deployment on combat missions.
The software flaws were particularly significant as the Baden-Württemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 seamen, which is half the crews of the old Bremen class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the ship is considerably overloaded, which reduces its efficiency and reduces the Navy's ability to make future improvements.
The 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz is estimated to weigh twice as much as the similar class of ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond the failures of the computer system, the cost of the project as a whole - including the training of the crew - also becomes a problem.
It is said to have reached an astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), compared with 2.2 billion at the start.
The problems of new frigates are of particular importance in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval strength is declining.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, acknowledged earlier this year that the navy is actually running out of ships capable of deploying.
The official said the situation had produced a snowball effect over time, as the old ships were decommissioned but no replacement ships were designated.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class could join the Navy.
The National Trust is keeping a close eye on the bat's secret life
New research in a region of the Scottish Highlands is seeking to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation efforts.
The study by researchers from the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-eared brown and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile studies using portable detectors.
Professional sound analysis will help to determine the frequency of bat calls and the activities of the different species.
A map and habitat report will be drawn up to give a detailed picture of their behaviour at the territorial level.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how these are used by each of these species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of grasslands and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work which affects their perch and leads to the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-killing paper and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from pet cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles on their flight path.
Responsible for the protection of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts who regularly conduct excavations, inspections at the perch and sometimes rescues.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the manager of the estate, says that the site is the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have a perfect place for bats", he said.
We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there's still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we're doing here and elsewhere will help us better understand what bats need to thrive. 
He stresses the importance of checking for bats before any property maintenance, as the accidental destruction of a single nest can result in the death of 400 females and young, or the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, head of the Bat Conservation Trust in Scotland, urged the public to help.
She said:  We still have a lot to learn about our bats and with regards to many of our species, we don't know what's going on in their populations at the moment. 
